## Architecture summary

**Event flow:** Every domain action (tip, go-live, KYC change, payout, private show request) publishes to a `notification.events` Kafka topic. The notification service consumes from this topic — giving you durability, replay, and zero coupling to the originating service.

**Notification Service core responsibilities:**
- **Consumer** — reads Kafka events, maps them to notification types
- **User preference lookup** — checks PostgreSQL for which channels the user has enabled per event type
- **Deduplication** — Redis key per `(userId, eventId)` with a short TTL prevents duplicate sends if Kafka re-delivers
- **Rate limiter** — Redis token bucket per user per channel (e.g. max 5 push/hour) prevents spam
- **Template engine** — renders HTML emails, WhatsApp approved templates, and push payloads from S3-stored templates
- **Dead letter queue (DLQ)** — failed deliveries retry with exponential backoff; after N retries, drop to DLQ for manual inspection
- **Delivery log** — PostgreSQL write of every sent/failed notification for audit and support

